author: Andrew_McAfee;
title: Are droids taking our jobs?

aws-transcripts.transcript: As it turns out, when tens of millions of people are unemployed or underemployed, there's a fair amount of interest in what technology might be doing to the labor force. And as I look at the conversation, it strikes me that it's focused on exactly the right topic. And at the same time, it's missing the point entirely. The topic that it's focused on the question is whether or not all these digital technologies are affecting people's ability to earn a living or to say it a little bit different way. Are the droids taking our jobs? And there's some evidence that they are. The great recession ended when American GDP resumed its kind of slow, steady march upward, and some other economic indicators also started to rebound. And they got kind of healthy kind of quickly. Corporate profits are quite high. In fact, if you include bank profits, they're higher than they've ever been, And business investment in gear, in equipment and hardware and software is at an all time high so that businesses are getting out their checkbooks. What they're not really doing is hiring, So this red line is the employment to population ratio.
